     by data-raw/precompile-vignette.R: edit the .orig and re-run that script;
     do not edit the generated file. -->

```{r, include = FALSE}
# fig.path is a file prefix (not a directory): R CMD check flags a
# vignettes/figure/ directory as a knitr leftover, but accepts the
# precomputed PNGs sitting next to the .Rmd.
knitr::opts_chunk$set(collapse = TRUE, comment = "#>",
                      fig.width = 7, fig.height = 4.5,
                      fig.path = "getting-started-")
# The estimation engines are optional dependencies; only run the fitting
# chunks when they are available so the vignette also builds without them.
has_trajer  <- requireNamespace("trajeR", quietly = TRUE)
has_flexmix <- requireNamespace("flexmix", quietly = TRUE)
has_lcmm    <- requireNamespace("lcmm", quietly = TRUE)
has_ggplot  <- requireNamespace("ggplot2", quietly = TRUE)

# trajeR prints optimizer progress (Starting Values / iter ... value ... /
# converged) while fitting -- some of it on stdout, some on stderr. Strip that
# chatter from the displayed output and message streams so the vignette shows
# results, not solver logs. The hooks see text with the `comment` prefix (#>)
# already applied, so match past it.
strip_chatter <- function(x) {
  lines <- strsplit(x, "\n", fixed = TRUE)[[1]]
  core  <- sub("^#>\\s?", "", lines)
  drop <- grepl(
    "^(iter\\s|initial\\s+value|final\\s+value|converged|Starting Values|Likelihood)",
    core) | grepl("^[0-9][0-9.eE+-]*$", core)
  lines <- lines[!drop]
  blank <- !nzchar(trimws(sub("^#>", "", lines)))
  lines <- lines[!(blank & c(FALSE, blank[-length(blank)]))]
  paste(lines, collapse = "\n")
}
default_output_hook  <- knitr::knit_hooks$get("output")
default_message_hook <- knitr::knit_hooks$get("message")
knitr::knit_hooks$set(
  output  = function(x, options) default_output_hook(strip_chatter(x), options),
  message = function(x, options) {
    x <- strip_chatter(x)
    if (!nzchar(trimws(sub("^#>", "", x)))) return(NULL)
    default_message_hook(x, options)
  }
)
```

`gbtmkit` turns group-based trajectory modeling (GBTM) into a reproducible
pipeline that follows the GRoLTS reporting checklist. Estimation is delegated to
interchangeable backends behind one interface, so the same workflow handles
binary and continuous outcomes, and the fit diagnostics (entropy, APPA, OCC,
group proportions) are computed the same way regardless of engine.

```{r setup}
library(gbtmkit)
```

## The data

The package ships two entirely synthetic datasets with known ground-truth
groups. `sim_binary` has a binary outcome measured on ten occasions, with four
latent trajectory shapes of mixed polynomial order: a linear rising group, a
cubic rise-peak-decline group, a cubic decline-trough-recovery group, and a
linear falling group:

```{r}
data("sim_binary", package = "gbtmkit")
head(sim_binary)
```

## Describe the model with a spec

`gbtm_spec()` records *what* to model -- the outcome and time columns (by name),
the id, and the outcome family -- and validates it, independent of which engine
will fit it.

```{r}
spec <- gbtm_spec(
  sim_binary,
  outcomes = paste0("y", 1:10),
  time     = paste0("t", 1:10),
  id       = "id",
  family   = "binomial"
)
spec
```

## Run the whole pipeline in one call

`run_gbtm_pipeline()` performs algorithm selection (when the engine offers a
choice), group-number selection, the polynomial-shape search with GRoLTS
acceptance criteria, and the final Hessian-on fit. Here we use a small search to
keep the vignette quick.

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
res <- run_gbtm_pipeline(
  spec,
  candidates = 2:5,     # consider 2 to 5 groups
  degree     = 2,       # quadratic while choosing the number of groups --
                        # with curved shapes, linear-only selection under-selects
  method     = "L",     # fix the algorithm (skip stage 1) for speed
  max_degree = 3,       # allow up to cubic in the shape search
  seed       = 1,
  verbose    = FALSE
)
res
```

The pipeline recovers the four planted groups. Everything each stage produced is
kept on the result object:

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
res$group_selection      # BIC for each candidate number of groups
```

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
summary(res)
```

## Inspect and plot

`gbtm_diagnostics()` gives the GRoLTS classification diagnostics, and
`plot_trajectories()` draws the fitted group trajectories with the observed
per-group means overlaid.

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
res$diagnostics$groups
```

```{r, eval = has_trajer && has_ggplot, fig.alt = "Fitted group trajectories"}
plot_trajectories(res$final_fit)
```

Per-subject group assignment (the analogue of exporting a group column) is in
`res$assignment`:

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
head(res$assignment)
```

## Run the stages individually

`run_gbtm_pipeline()` is a convenience wrapper. For full control you can run each
GRoLTS stage yourself and inspect the result before moving on -- this is exactly
what the wrapper does internally.

### Stage 1: choose the estimation algorithm

trajeR offers `"L"`, `"EM"` and `"EMIRLS"`; the one with the lowest BIC is
selected. (Engines with a single optimizer skip this stage.)

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
algo <- select_algorithm(spec, n_groups = 2, degrees = c(1, 1))
algo
```

### Stage 2: choose the number of groups

The number of groups is chosen by BIC over a set of candidates. Quadratic
shapes are used while sweeping: with curved trajectories like these,
linear-only selection under-selects the number of groups:

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
groups <- select_n_groups(spec, candidates = 2:5, degree = 2, method = "L")
groups
```

### Stage 3: search polynomial shapes

The polynomial shapes are searched for the chosen number of groups, then the
GRoLTS acceptance criteria (PMS > 0.05, APPA > 0.70, OCC >= 5) are applied.
(The one-call pipeline above searched up to cubic; here we cap the search at
quadratic to keep the vignette quick.)

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
shapes <- evaluate_shapes(spec, n_groups = groups$best, method = "L",
                          max_degree = 2, verbose = FALSE)
apply_grolts_criteria(shapes)
```

### Stage 4: fit the final model

The final model is fit with the Hessian on, so the fit carries standard
errors, and the diagnostics and per-subject assignment are read off it. Here
we use the lowest-BIC shape found by the search:

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
fit <- fit_gbtm(spec, n_groups = groups$best, degrees = shapes$best, method = "L")
gbtm_diagnostics(fit)
head(gbtm_assign(fit))
```

## Continuous outcomes

The same pipeline handles continuous outcomes: switch the family to
`"gaussian"` (mapped to a censored-normal model) and point the spec at a
continuous dataset. `sim_continuous` has the same four shape types on a
continuous scale.

We fit cubic shapes in all four groups (in a real analysis the shape search
refines the per-group degrees, as above). Shape misspecification can push a fit
into a degenerate local optimum where a group ends up empty -- on this data,
forcing *linear* shapes (`degrees = rep(1, 4)`) with the `"L"` optimizer does
exactly that. If it happens, `plot_trajectories()` / `gbtm_predict()` warn you;
switching the method (`"EM"` recovers all four groups here) or revisiting the
shapes fixes it.

```{r, eval = has_trajer}
data("sim_continuous", package = "gbtmkit")
cspec <- gbtm_spec(
  sim_continuous,
  outcomes = paste0("y", 1:10),
  time     = paste0("t", 1:10),
  id       = "id",
  family   = "gaussian"
)
cfit <- fit_gbtm(cspec, n_groups = 4, degrees = rep(3, 4), method = "L")
gbtm_diagnostics(cfit)$entropy
```

`plot_trajectories()` works the same way; for a continuous outcome the fitted
lines and the observed points are on the outcome's own scale (means, not
probabilities):

```{r, eval = has_trajer && has_ggplot, fig.alt = "Fitted continuous group trajectories"}
plot_trajectories(cfit)
```

## Choosing an engine

Everything above used the default engine, `trajeR`. Estimation is pluggable:
every fitting function (`gbtm_fit()`, the stage functions, and
`run_gbtm_pipeline()`) takes an `engine` argument, and the registry tells you
what each backend offers:

```{r}
gbtm_engines()
sapply(gbtm_engines(), gbtm_engine_families)
sapply(gbtm_engines(), gbtm_engine_per_group_degrees)
```

The three backends make different trade-offs:

| | `trajeR` (default) | `flexmix` | `lcmm` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Families | binomial, gaussian, poisson, beta | binomial, gaussian, poisson | binomial, gaussian |
| Optimizers | `"L"`, `"EM"`, `"EMIRLS"` (stage 1 picks one) | EM (fixed) | Marquardt (fixed) |
| Per-group degrees | yes | no -- one order for all groups | no -- one order for all groups |
| Notes | reference GBTM implementation | fast EM on large data | `hlme()`; binary via a thresholds link |

The pipeline adapts automatically: for a single-optimizer engine stage 1 is
skipped, and for a uniform-degree engine the stage-3 shape search sweeps
uniform shapes (degree 1 for all groups, degree 2 for all groups, ...) instead
of per-group combinations.

Switching engine is one argument -- here the same 4-group cubic model on the
binary data with each backend:

```{r, eval = has_trajer && has_flexmix && has_lcmm, warning = FALSE}
fits <- list(
  trajeR  = fit_gbtm(spec, engine = "trajeR",  n_groups = 4,
                     degrees = rep(3, 4), method = "L", hessian = FALSE),
  flexmix = fit_gbtm(spec, engine = "flexmix", n_groups = 4,
                     degrees = rep(3, 4), seed = 1),
  lcmm    = fit_gbtm(spec, engine = "lcmm",    n_groups = 4,
                     degrees = rep(3, 4), seed = 1)
)
sapply(fits, function(f) {
  d <- gbtm_diagnostics(f)
  c(entropy = round(d$entropy, 3), min_appa = round(min(d$groups$appa), 3))
})
```

All three engines find the same four groups with comparable classification
quality. One caution: **compare BIC within an engine, never across engines** --
each backend defines its likelihood differently (lcmm's thresholds link even
fits a different model family), so their absolute BIC values are not on a
common scale. Use BIC to pick the number of groups and shape *given* an
engine; use the classification diagnostics (entropy, APPA, OCC) to sanity-check
a fit from any engine.

## Notes

* **Engine-agnostic by design.** The pipeline talks only to a small set of
  accessors (`gbtm_bic()`, `gbtm_posterior()`, `gbtm_group_sizes()`, ...), so
  additional backends can be added without changing the workflow.
* **Built to scale.** The shape search runs the fits with the Hessian off
  (needed only for the final model's standard errors), defaults to a greedy
  stepwise strategy, and supports a `time_budget`, `max_fits`, and on-disk
  `checkpoint`ing so large problems run unattended and bounded.
```
